:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Ethic question</span><hr size=1> I'm just wondering, maybe I'm making a big fuss out of something.  Say you had a group and an item falls which would is very good for warriors and paladins but useable by other melee yet weighs 3 stones.  If you were a monk, would you roll on it?  Most people roll with NBG and the monk wasn't going to roll but said 'I will roll for a friend'.  Well, the monk won and I said I thought it was unfair giving the item to someone else and he said 'Well... I'll use it'.  I've never played a monk, but I'm pretty sure I've never seen a monk who would use an item that weighs 3 stones (although it did grant 5 strength).  I personnally think the monk will give the item to someone else but it just lead me to think.<br>
<br>
Do many people function like this?  I once did the mistake (I realized myself) of rolling for an item that wasn't meant for me, but I lost the roll and since then, I've been a major need before greed pain in the ass, but do many people do this, roll on items which would advantage someone else in a group to either sell, trade or give it to a friend?  I won't mention any names here, but to say the least, I wasn't the least bit impressed as it would have been a very good item for me and I could have easily used it up until our guild is strong enough to raid a plane but I came up second on the roll.<br>
<br>
What do people here think, was the monk right in going against the need before greed rule? (assuming he won't wear it, which I doubt he will as he had changed his claim from giving it to using it).  What would you people have done? Refused to give him the item, blacklisted him and his guild or nothing at all?<br>
<br>
Just an FYI, the item was a cloak, 8ac, 5strenght, 10 save magic which weighed 3 stones.  I give the stats as I think it was given to someone who posts here and I'm curious as to what the person will say to defend themself, but I know it certainly led me to reconsider the way I call an item which I can use, but might or will not in a group. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=aleira>Aleira</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 10:51:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> Sad to say, but most likely he didn't really intend to use it. 3 Stone is a lot for a Monk to bear, and his initial reaction indicates that he had no intention of using it. If he wasn't going to give it to a friend, it wouldn't surprise me to find that he had sold it at auction.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, things like this can happen when loot gets doled out. It's sad, but it's hard to avoid 100% of the time.<br>
<br>
However, if the group knew about the Monk rolling beforehand, any objections should have been raised before the roll. If they don't object to his rolling on it, then they cannot realistically object to his winning.<br>
<br>
Communication is the key. <p>Aleira
Magician of the 6th Summoning
Tailoring (19)
Firiona Vie</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uaeonii.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aeonii</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 11:14:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> I try not to post much anymore, lest I get myself in trouble <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  , but NBG is one of our guild's primary philosophies.  And it happens that I was pondering on this very topic last night - wandering thoughts for a traveling soul...<br>
<br>
My humble opinion is that if someone is not a party to the event that led to obtaining the item (killing the mob that dropped it), then they should not have someone act as a surrogate to obtain it, nor should anyone act as a surrogate for someone else.  This is when partied in pick-up groups (various people together).<br>
<br>
The only time that I feel that it would be appropriate is if someone came to a group stating that they were specifically, explicitly looking for the item in question, *and* the group agreed to it.  This would paticularly be reasonable if the ones trying to obtain the item were not guilded and the item was hard to obtain alone.<br>
<br>
The only other scenario I think it would be appropriate is if the item was dropped more than once, and everyone in the party that wanted it had obtained it during the current battle.<br>
<br>
For your particular situation...  If the item was nice, go back and try to obtain it.  It is frustrating to be in the situation that you were in, but there are things to consider...<br>
<br>
I percieve that the monk was allowed to roll because the odds looked like they would not win anyway.  But on the other hand, at worst there was a one in six chance that they would.  It seems in this situation, the easy thing was to go ahead and let the monk roll with the hopes that they would lose the roll anyway.  The hard thing would have been to tell the monk &quot;no&quot; and try to work out other another compromise for something the monk obviously wanted out of percieved greed.<br>
<br>
Sometimes it's best to let bygones be bygones.  There is no telling what the monk will do with it, and at this point, it is probably mute.  Blame leads to pain, as someone dear to me is fond of saying.  It holds true.  Then we have to go back and eat humble pie <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  .  With or without whipped cream.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Lol.  Learn from this experience and carry the education with you in the future my friend.<br>
<br>
May your adventures today be better than your journeys of yesterday...<br>
<br>
Go well<br>
Æonii  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufeneant.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Feneant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 182<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 11:34:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> The reason we let him take it was that technically, he could use it, we all knew he wouldn't, but he said he would so how could we stop him.  We will get more of the item, it was just a drop off a mob we saw, we didn't know we would get it, but I should mention that the mob was about 40-45 while we were between 30-35 and it took everything we had to kill it.<br>
<br>
I do know one thing, I will never be in a party with him again or with the person who told him to roll as I have no choice but to say that they have no honor.  I have played with a few in the guild he is in before and they had always stressed a strong NBG philosophy, no questions asked, if someone could use the item, they took it and no objections were raised. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 95<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 11:59:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> Well, I've played a monk up to 60 and am playing one again now.  I'd say it would really depend on the item.  If it was the best item in it's class in the game, I might use it.  Weapons for monks are typically heavy; eg. the fighting batons are 2.0 each and well worth using two of them even if it puts you overweight.  The nice 2HB's often weigh 10.0 and are also well worth using.  So, unless you can be specific on the item, it's really hard to say if a monk would use it or not.  If it was a nice weapon, I'd say almost certainly worth it.<br>
<br>
OTH, the way I do loot when running a group is that if you put in a class-claim for an item (ie. I deserve this more than others because my class gets far more benefit from it than yours and I'd use it 100% of the time), then that person needs to hand down the item he upgraded.  Otherwise, the class-claimer gets both an upgrade and a trade item.  If it's not worth handing down the old item, then it's not worth class-claiming the new one.  This cuts out buddy-looters from class items.<br>
<br>
I like &quot;commie&quot; looting best: all trade-items and all scrounge loot goes to one person with autosplit turned off.  That person then does an equitable split before the group breaks up or before adding/removing a groupie, either after selling off all the junk or after adding the value of the junk to the pool and splitting it then.  This is often hard to do in a pickup group and many people don't like to be the comisar.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that's just how I run things.  My advice to you is that when making a pickup group, lay down the law on loot in advance (eg. NBG with hand-down.  I will resolve all loot disputes as group leader).  This isn't being mean or greedy, it's just making the group's goals clear -- part of good leading.  If you're not leading, be sure to ask what the looting style is and also ask the leader to act as final loot arbiter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uhueth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hueth</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 12:01:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Ethic question</span><hr size=1> ___________________________________________<br>
