Haldrim the Charmer  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufeneant.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Feneant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 183<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 12:05:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> To be clear... I was not looting and this was not a pick up party, is was 3 members of my guild fighting and the monk asked to join us.  There were no loot rules defined as there is no loot on Luclin almost, we just followed our normal loot rules.  As to what was the item, I did say what it is, its' a cape with 8ac, 5str and 10 magic resistance which for a warrior is very good as it contains strength and magic resistance on the same item.  When we are fighting for loot and not experience, Im usually the master looter and we've never had this type of problem before since we normally play the same group in the guild.  With the others outside the guild I play with, its need before greed with either commie or ffa with honor.  This was the first time I was faced with this type of situation but im sure most will agree that paladin and warrior would have had dibs on this item. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utheycallmetasker.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Theycallmetasker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 1:26:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> commie looting hah!</span><hr size=1> Ok Bjond now i know your an ex tunare player! Har Har<br>
<br>
As far as looting in groups goes, its a tuff call, different people have different views and when they clash over loots...<br>
<br>
I personally cant stand NBG, so many times Ive seen players scream NBG then learned later that they have sold or traded the items off. NBG is way too easy to abuse if you dont know the people you are grouped with well. However if you do know the people you are grouped with then NBG works great.<br>
<br>
Assuming you are grouped with some people that dont know each other, If you do 25% of the work killing a mob, do you deserve a 25% shot at the loot? If the monk in question turns around and sells that cloak to buy a fighting baton, is that wrong?  Remember, even if you lost a roll on an item, you still had a fair chance at it.<br>
<br>
The best way to deal with this issue is to make sure everyone understands the rules before the loot drops, Aleira said it best, Communication is the key.<br>
<br>
Tasker, lvl 41 Iksar Monk<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=dalninil>Dalninil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 1:28:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> Depends 3 stones is alot for a monk.. but not to much if you are going to use NBG be prepared for anyone that can use it to roll on it. It has MR on it so it could even be banked until AC drop isn't an issue and resists are needed.<br>
<br>
There are 8 million ways to justify taking an item if you want to do so, it's really up to you. You were a guild group you could have even said that all loot in this group goes to the guild. (shrug) you lost a roll when you allowed someone to roll on an item. Happens every day, don't get mad just go kill the mob again. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uquillionthegnome.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quillion the Gnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 1:52:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ethic question</span><hr size=1> Yep, Tasker and Aleira are correct. Stating the looting rules clearly and then agreeing upon them before the hunt begins is the best way to avoid looting conflicts.<br>
<br>
Different folks are going to have a different idea of whats fair of course, but typically folks will give in to the majority and if they strongly disagree they can chose not to group.<br>
<br>
Just remember to inform new additions to the group as folks come and go!<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=bardicj>Bardic J</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 4:00:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> hmm..</span><hr size=1> Funny Bjond, I posted the same idea for looting on the Saryn msg boards long ago and I got flamed straight to hell, NO ONE liked the idea. <br>
<br>
Well I think one caster did heh. I had always been pro NBG, but then I started to see that it was somewhat flawed. A warrior wielding a Wurmslayer and a Lam Blade in the offhand would get defaulted another Lam blade because it was best for him to replace his slayer. So he'd get the blade, and the next day he would be in north freeport auctioning off his Wurmslayer for 5k (back when they sold for that much). So in effect he wins a new weapon and 5k and the group who helped him get it wins nothing.<br>
<br>
Things like this happened alot and the more I saw it the more I thought it was wrong, I didn't play a caster either, I was a Ogre Warrior, so any claims I was a biased caster could be thrown out of the window. So I talked about the idea that when a character is defaulted something, they must giveup whatever they are replacing it with. Sure sometimes the old item would suck compared to the new one, which is fine, but sometimes the old item may be very close in value to the new one, which is ALSO fine. Anyway everyone hated the idea, as a group leader I enforced this two times before I just gave up the idea as it led to many heated arguements.<br>
<br>
The second and last case of this was a Paladin who was wearing Gauntlets of the Black, and Deepwater gauntlets droped in karnor castle. He wanted it to be defaulted to him, and I agreed that they should be, as long as he let the group roll on his old Gauntlets. He FREAKED, said I was a greedy bastard and that he woudn't do it... so I told him tough luck and the Gnome Enchanter won shiney new gauntlets. After the hole thing went to the boards, everyone agreed that is was a bad and &quot;lame greedy&quot; idea for rolling, and they pretty much all agreed that people should be able to keep and sell their old gear even when they are defaulted a item.<br>
<br>
I've thought about trying this idea here for my groups, but I am almost scared to even bother with it again if history is going to repeat itself heh.<br>
<br>
Oh and with the Monk, I'd of simply held him to his first comment, I've done this before also. <br>
It won't make you popular, but denying people loot for any reason, valid or not won't make you popular. The easy route is to simply let the loot freaks get whatever they want, take the hard route <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 6:07:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmm.</span><hr size=1> 8ac is nice, but not really a big deal.  STR doesn't much matter for any class, so arguments on that stat don't hold up.  10 MR is incredible, though.  It's well worth 3.0 weight.  When fighting casters, I would often go horribly overweight to hype my resists.  His first comment was that it was for a friend, so I would not have put him in the random.  Buddy-looting is only OK when the item goes full-random.  Then you can do whatever you like with it.<br>
<br>
The idea behind class-restrictive looting is that you want to help people outfit their characters.  It's not a means for increasing your chances at obtaining stuff to trade.  Some form of NBG is best.  Think about it.  If you do full random on, say, a nice warrior item and won, would you turn around and sell that item to the warrior you rolled against? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0> at: 12/29/01 6:36:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/29/01 7:25:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm.</span><hr size=1> I am a huge fan of need-before-greed (NBG if anyone doesn't know the appreviation) but I also know that looting styles on this point are an open question.  I would never join a guild where NBG was even a question, and I think it's natural your guild functions that way, but...when you invite someone from outside the guild into the group you are probably a lot safer out-lining how things work in advance.  I normally take it as a given that if I join a group of three in progress, all from the same guild, I am expected to follow their policies.  But I'm not sure that attitude can be assumed.<br>
<br>
I think it's a shame the monk rolled on something he probably (in my opinion) isn't going to use himself.  Or if he does, at most, it will be a situational piece equipment.  However, I think it's also a shame he saw a nice item drop and then had people tell him he had no rightful claim to it, if he hadn't known in advance the group was working that way.  Always best to take a moment to clarify these things.  It doesn't really take long.<br>
<br>
Valquiss<br>
<br>
P.S. There are levels and layers to NBG also.  For example, what if someone would get considerably more use out of an item than another person in the party, but both would honestly use it?  I have a set of int gear (earrings, rings, a held item etc.) I use only for trade skills, prefering charisma stuff for fighting (I am an enchanter) but trade skills are pretty important to me.  So I would definitely use a better int item even if I wasn't wearing it full time.  But I'd feel bad rolling against a mage or a wizard or a necro for it, if they intended to wear the item full time.  I don't have any hard and fast advice on this point, it's just something to think about.  That monk might have the cloak sitting around his bank account for backup in raids where there will be a lot of casters.  But better there, or on the back of some warrior 24-7?   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umidwestpatriot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MidwestPatriot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 67<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/31/01 2:50:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=975.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <br>
Wow, tough questions.  I have to agree with many of you.  <br>
<br>
I'll pick a path to talk about, since there are so many ways to go with this thread.  And loot rules are up to the leader of the group you join.<br>
<br>
Since I practice trade skills it is hard to get a chance at int or wis items when there are any int or wis casters in a group, as most people don't practice trades and do not understand the importance of int and wisdom in such things.<br>
<br>
So, I end up having to trade or buy the int items, get hand-me-downs, or pray that there is not an int/wis caster in the group when a nice one falls.  <br>
