<br>
I am a big fan of NBG in guild groups.  You join a guild, you adventure with them and you all work for the common good (generally).  If you adventure in a place where warrior stuff drops, it goes to the warrior.  No worries if you are a rogue, since you trust that eventually you'll be in a similar situation with the same folks where rogue stuff drops.  So if you are running around with guildies, NBG every time, no question.<br>
<br>
It's pick-up groups where NBG breaks down.<br>
<br>
You are a caster (any kind, doesn't matter) and are invited by another group to go and camp the Frenzy room in LGuk.  Then the FBSS drops and you are not allowed to roll on it since you are not a melee.  Whoa!  You all fought equally hard and likely you'll never lay eyes on one another again.  [of course if you are invited down there and they lay out the rules ahead of time, you have only yourself to blame]<br>
<br>
Now, I'm a big believer in the &quot;first right of sale&quot; for pick-up groups.  You roll randomly for the item, and the people who can use it get to bid on it for a reasonable price.  Perfect?  Easily enforceable?  No way, but it beats some of the NBG abuses.<br>
<br>
Now to be fair, FV is different.  There are few enough people here that once you get above 40 or so, you are almost bound to know everyone's name.  Heck, I'm only 18th level and I think I know the better portion of my contemporaries on sight.  In the best of all worlds, your reputation and habits will precede you and a zone-wide NBG may be a possibility.<br>
